{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472975"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1683"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1683"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.26,0.06,0.2,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1683"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49009"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1683"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1683"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34027"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"890"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11594"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13483"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49009"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-month-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents, who are concerned about a lump on his abdomen (Image). This has been present since birth, and his parents think that it might be getting larger. They have also noticed intermittent wetness around the lump. His mother\u0027s pregnancy was uncomplicated, and all antenatal investigations during pregnancy were noted to be normal, including morphological scans. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lump is located in the midline of the lower abdomen, just above the umbilicus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Patent vitello-intestinal duct","Patent urachus","Strawberry naevus","Umbilical hernia","Umbilical granuloma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis swelling is most likely a \u003Cstrong\u003Epatent urachus\u003C/strong\u003E. The urachus is an embryonic structure that connects the bladder to the umbilicus and normally closes shortly before birth. If it remains partially or completely patent, it can lead to urachal abnormalities, which are not uncommon. These abnormalities can present as a cyst, sinus, or fistula. In this case, the intermittent discharge of urine, as reported by the parents, is characteristic of a partially patent urachal sinus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epatent vitello-intestinal duct\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as the omphalomesenteric duct) is extremely rare, and it is very unlikely an infant with such a defect would survive into childhood without surgical correction. It typically presents with umbilical drainage more consistent with bowel contents rather than urine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Estrawberry naevus\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of vascular birthmark that appears as a raised, red area on the skin. It would not discharge fluid and typically has a different appearance from the defect described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eumbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E should be covered by skin and would increase in size with increased intra-abdominal pressure (such as crying, coughing, or straining). It can potentially be reduced and does not discharge any fluid, unlike the presentation in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eumbilical granuloma\u003C/strong\u003E typically results from a low-grade infection of the umbilical stump and presents soon after cord separation as red, friable granulation tissue. It would not discharge urine and usually has a different appearance from a urachal abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosing a patent urachus in this case is the combination of the midline abdominal mass present since birth and the intermittent wetness, which suggests urinary discharge. Further investigations, such as ultrasound or a voiding cystourethrogram, may be necessary to confirm the diagnosis and determine the extent of the urachal patency. Management typically involves surgical correction to prevent complications such as recurrent infections or rarely, malignant transformation later in life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Wetness around a urachal sinus suggests persistent patency with the bladder.","A patent urachus is a congenital anomaly where the embryonic connection between the bladder and umbilicus fails to close completely.","Urachal abnormalities can present as a cyst, sinus, or fistula, often with intermittent urinary discharge."],"references":["Briggs KB. Patent Urachus [Internet]. StatPearls [Internet]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2020. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557723/","Snyder CL. Current management of umbilical abnormalities and related anomalies. Sem Ped Surg 2007; 16:41-49."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34027"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1683"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18676"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18676"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"ht